theoretical curiosity for the millennium that we refer to as the Middle Ages. What does it mean to adopt a theoretical attitude? Have there been cultural differences or changes in the meaning of curiositas? This is where two attitudes collide: curiositas as misguided curiosity and as a natural longing in the sense of an anthropological existential.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 4aKultur- und Wissenschaftsgeschichte. 4aMediävistik. 4aPhilosophie. 4aTheoretische Neugierde.  aTheoretical curiosity.  ahistory of science and culture.  amedieval studies.  aphilosophy.1 aConzelmann, Delphine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDi Maio, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEbermeier, Verena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdelheit, Amos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEgel, Nikolaus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEusterschulte, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFischer, Susanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriedrich, Matthias, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreule, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHellmeier, Paul D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHommers, Jeannet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKapriev, Georgi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlein, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLamprakis, Alexander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLangeloh, Jacob, econtributor.